<!-- awf:section overview -->
# Working with awf

This project's skills, agents, docs, and `AGENTS.md` are generated by awf from the committed
`.awf/` config tree. Every rendered file carries a `GENERATED by awf` banner ŌĆö never hand-edit one;
change `.awf/` and re-render. This guide covers working with an already-adopted project; adopting
awf into a new repo is documented in the awf project itself.

awf also always renders `.awf/memory/.gitignore` ŌĆö a self-ignoring gitignore that keeps the working-memory directory (per-effort session-state files, described in the agent guide's working-memory section) out of version control. The `.gitignore` itself is rendered and drift-checked; the directory's contents never are.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section commands -->
## Commands

- `awf sync` ŌĆö re-render every artifact from `.awf/` and update `.awf/awf.lock`.
- `awf check` ŌĆö fail if any rendered file has drifted from the config (also gates the schema version).
- `awf add <kind> <name>` / `awf remove <kind> <name>` ŌĆö toggle a skill, agent, doc, domain, target, bootstrap, or hooks artifact.
- `awf list` ŌĆö show the catalog and what is enabled.
- `awf new adr "<title>"` ŌĆö scaffold the next ADR.
- `awf new skill <name> "<description>"` / `awf new agent <name> "<description>"` ŌĆö scaffold a project-local skill/agent (rendered from awf's base template plus a `content` part you author).
- `awf upgrade` ŌĆö migrate the config tree after upgrading the awf binary.
- `awf audit` ŌĆö report Conventional-Commits / workflow-conformance findings over the branch (advisory).
- `awf invariants` ŌĆö report Implemented-ADR `inv:` slugs that lack a backing comment in source.
- `awf commit-gate <file>` ŌĆö validate one commit message (used by a commit-msg hook).
- `awf changelog` ŌĆö query the changelog by version or range.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section config-and-overrides -->
## Config and overrides

Configuration lives in `.awf/`: a `config.yaml` skeleton (prefix, vars, enable arrays, targets,
audit, invariants), per-artifact sidecar YAMLs, and convention parts. To change one section of a
rendered artifact, drop a **convention part** at `.awf/<kind>/parts/<target>/<section>.md` (for a
doc, `.awf/docs/parts/<name>/<section>.md`; for an always-on singleton,
`.awf/parts/<kind>/<section>.md`). A part **replaces that section's body** and inherits the rest of
the template default. Convention parts are raw input: their content renders verbatim and is never
run through the template engine ŌĆö see [the documentation standard](doc-standard.md) for the
authoring rules.

**Project-local skills and agents.** Beyond overriding catalog artifacts, you can define your own.
`awf new skill <name> "<description>"` enables a name that is not in awf's standard catalog, writes a
declaring sidecar, and drops a `content` convention part for you to author. awf renders it from a
built-in base template ŌĆö once per enabled target ŌĆö so a skill you define once is emitted for every
agent harness you target. Edit its body at `.awf/skills/parts/<name>/content.md` (agents:
`.awf/agents/parts/<name>/content.md`); the sidecar's `data.description` becomes its frontmatter
description.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section placeholders -->
## Placeholders in overrides

A convention part may splice in awf-derived values through the `awf:`-namespaced placeholder
{{ "{{=awf:KEY}}" }}. It is a literal substitution (not the template engine), so a stray `{{ "{{" }}` in
prose stays inert. A key is available only when its value is **non-empty** this render; an unknown
or empty key, or a malformed near-miss, is a hard error that names the available keys. The keys:

| key | renders |
|---|---|
| `commitScopeList` | the allowed commit-scope names, comma-separated |
| `commitScopeTable` | a markdown table of scope names and meanings |
| `commitScopeSentence` | a one-sentence statement of the allowed scopes |
| `invariantMarkerSentence` | a sentence naming the invariant comment markers by file type |
| `invariantMarkerTable` | a markdown table of file globs and their invariant comment markers |
| `prefix` | the project's artifact prefix |
| `gateCmd` | the configured pre-commit gate command |
| `checkCmd` | the configured drift-check command |

To write the placeholder syntax literally in a part (for documentation), put a backslash before it:
{{ "\\{{=awf:commitScopeTable}}" }} renders as the literal {{ "{{=awf:commitScopeTable}}" }}.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section sync-and-drift -->
## Keeping in sync

After any edit to `.awf/`, run `awf sync` to re-render, then `awf check` to confirm no drift, and
commit the rendered files alongside the config change. `awf check` compares each rendered file's
template and config against `.awf/awf.lock`; a mismatch is `stale` drift. Wire `awf check` and your
gate into CI so drift and rule violations block a merge.
<!-- awf:end -->
